WEBVTT

00:01.734 --> 00:04.066
So, Jose will handle the story
on the cafeteria food.

00:04.133 --> 00:07.000
Amanda, I need you to cover
the interview with Principal Tweedy.

00:07.066 --> 00:10.233
And I would like to thank Ms. Dew,
our returning faculty advisor.

00:10.467 --> 00:12.000
It's great to see you
back from sabbatical.

00:12.066 --> 00:13.467
Everyone, a big hand for Ms. Dew.

00:13.533 --> 00:15.467
[APPLAUSE]

00:15.533 --> 00:17.400
Okay, everyone, I'm going
to need you to e-mail me

00:17.467 --> 00:19.433
your stories tomorrow
by 9:00 a.m.

00:20.000 --> 00:21.066
Thank you.

00:21.633 --> 00:23.867
Sorry I'm late, Gordo.
So, what's my story?

00:24.367 --> 00:28.033
Foreign intrigue?
Internal affairs? Gonzo journalism?

00:28.200 --> 00:29.934
Whoa. Um...

00:30.300 --> 00:31.934
I guess I forgot to assign you one.

00:32.233 --> 00:33.533
A big fat nada?

00:34.066 --> 00:36.066
Sorry, Lizzie, but your name
wasn't on the sign-up sheet.

00:36.133 --> 00:37.367
It must have slipped my mind.

00:37.467 --> 00:39.967
[SIGHS] Miranda was supposed to
sign me up, but she's sick.

00:40.567 --> 00:42.567
So, you can't think of
any ideas for me?

00:42.700 --> 00:44.033
I'm fresh out of ideas.

00:46.867 --> 00:49.600
Great, now he decides
to stop being brilliant.

00:50.033 --> 00:51.300
You might want to try Ms. Dew.

00:52.500 --> 00:53.533
Good luck.

00:54.100 --> 00:55.100
[SIGHS]

00:57.800 --> 00:59.033
-Ms. Dew?
-[GASPS]

00:59.934 --> 01:01.967
Um, I didn't get an assignment,

01:02.033 --> 01:04.467
so I was wondering
if you had any ideas for me.

01:04.633 --> 01:07.000
Well, no one's asked me
for advice in years.

01:07.734 --> 01:10.867
You know, I used to be
the advice columnist
for my school newspaper.

01:11.333 --> 01:12.867
You used to give people advice?

01:13.266 --> 01:15.567
I did. You know,

01:16.233 --> 01:20.166
I bet I could be the advice columnist
for the e-zine.

01:20.400 --> 01:23.233
Or... Or I could be
the advice columnist for the e-zine.

01:24.066 --> 01:25.667
Well, that's an excellent idea.

01:26.900 --> 01:28.233
That was actually helpful.

01:28.300 --> 01:30.200
Maybe I don't give
Ms. Dew enough credit.

01:30.533 --> 01:34.500
[SNIFFING] Lizzie?
Do you smell mothballs?

01:35.433 --> 01:36.700
Or maybe not.

01:39.333 --> 01:42.467
So, you're looking at the school's
new advice columnist, Gordo.

01:42.567 --> 01:46.333
You? [LAUGHS] You don't give advice,
you take it.

01:46.400 --> 01:48.567
Oh, I've got plenty of advice.

01:48.867 --> 01:50.433
Just nothing I can say out loud.

01:51.533 --> 01:52.900
Oh, but that's where you're wrong.

01:53.000 --> 01:56.133
And my first piece of advice
is for you to let me have the job

01:56.200 --> 01:57.633
because if I don't take it,

02:00.266 --> 02:01.500
Ms. Dew will.

02:03.600 --> 02:04.633
You're hired.

02:05.500 --> 02:07.700
[THEME SONG PLAYING]

02:47.934 --> 02:49.333
Um, you're late.

02:49.433 --> 02:51.700
Uh, I know. I was busy copying these.

02:51.934 --> 02:53.000
What is all this?

02:53.300 --> 02:55.400
GORDO: Um, people who were
asking for advice,

02:55.467 --> 02:58.867
I put a small ad up on our web page
and we were flooded with e-mail.

02:59.934 --> 03:02.033
Either these kids
have me confused with Santa,

03:02.100 --> 03:04.100
or a lot of people
need help at school.

03:05.400 --> 03:07.734
This is so cool.
I can totally do this.

03:08.300 --> 03:09.300
"Dear Lizzie..."

03:09.367 --> 03:11.400
PARKER: <i>My little sister</i>
<i>is incredibly annoying.</i>

03:11.467 --> 03:13.367
She goes through all my stuff.

03:13.500 --> 03:15.867
-Who's Gordo?
-Give me that!

03:17.800 --> 03:21.433
She listens in on my phone calls
and is a total pain.

03:22.600 --> 03:23.934
Cut it out!

03:24.200 --> 03:25.200
[GROANS]

03:25.266 --> 03:27.800
But my parents think
she's totally adorable.

03:27.867 --> 03:29.066
What do I do?

03:29.133 --> 03:32.333
Signed, I want to be an only child.

03:35.100 --> 03:36.100
So?

03:36.967 --> 03:38.266
"Dear Only Child..."

03:38.333 --> 03:40.400
-[KNOCKING AT DOOR]
-PARKER'S SISTER: Hey, let me in!
Come on.

03:40.467 --> 03:42.500
LIZZIE: <i>"Little sisters</i>
<i>are always annoying </i>

03:42.567 --> 03:44.333
<i>"and you'll never </i>
<i>get your parents to believe you."</i>

03:44.400 --> 03:46.133
PARKER'S SISTER: Parker! Let me in!

03:46.233 --> 03:49.166
LIZZIE: <i>"Get a lock for your room </i>
<i>and look for an out-of-state college."</i>

03:49.233 --> 03:50.233
PARKER'S SISTER: Let me in!

03:50.367 --> 03:52.266
"Good luck. Lizzie."

03:52.400 --> 03:54.400
-Not bad.
-Not bad?

03:54.667 --> 03:56.000
Gordo, that was totally good.

03:56.767 --> 03:58.066
I think I found my thing.

03:58.300 --> 03:59.767
It's really more of a calling.

04:00.000 --> 04:01.300
I think I can make a difference.

04:01.367 --> 04:04.100
Just save all the touchy-feely stuff
for your column

04:04.166 --> 04:07.967
which, by the way, is due tomorrow,
9:00 a.m., no excuses.

04:08.367 --> 04:09.734
Yes, sir, Mr. Editor.

04:10.467 --> 04:11.567
One nation...

04:12.467 --> 04:13.533
Sorry, I'm late, but my...

04:13.600 --> 04:15.266
ALL: Indivisible,

04:15.333 --> 04:18.633
-with liberty and justice for all.
-[BURPING]

04:19.300 --> 04:20.767
[LAUGHTER]

04:24.000 --> 04:26.800
Mr. Burton, your antics
have just earned you

04:26.867 --> 04:28.367
a trip to the principal's office.

04:29.500 --> 04:30.533
Off you go.

04:30.600 --> 04:31.600
[SIGHS]

04:34.033 --> 04:36.934
MS. CHAPMAN I don't want to hear it
this morning, Mr. McGuire.

04:37.000 --> 04:38.367
Just take your seat.

04:40.133 --> 04:42.000
Who does Adam Burton think he is?

04:42.066 --> 04:47.100
I mean, everyone knows that burping
the pledge is my trademark move.

04:47.367 --> 04:48.533
Relax.

04:49.467 --> 04:52.300
The guy may do good work,
but you're the king.

04:53.033 --> 04:54.100
Thank you.

04:55.000 --> 04:56.133
For now anyway.

04:56.767 --> 04:57.800
[CHUCKLES]

05:00.433 --> 05:01.834
What took you so long?

05:01.900 --> 05:04.367
Well, everybody kept coming up to me,
asking me for advice.

05:04.667 --> 05:05.834
I think I'm a hit.

05:05.900 --> 05:07.200
Oh! Not just a hit.

05:07.266 --> 05:10.033
Try 500 hits to the web page
since this morning.

05:10.600 --> 05:13.900
I got to admit that your advice column
was a stroke of brilliance.

05:14.000 --> 05:15.000
[CHUCKLES]

05:15.500 --> 05:17.433
Memorize everything about this moment.

05:17.667 --> 05:19.433
Gordo just called me brilliant.

05:19.700 --> 05:22.200
Oh, that letter by
Clean Tween this morning...

05:25.533 --> 05:28.300
Dear Lizzie, my best friend
needs a stronger deodorant

05:28.367 --> 05:31.000
as she isn't exactly
springtime fresh after practice.

05:31.633 --> 05:32.834
Should I tell her?

05:36.467 --> 05:38.200
Signed, Clean Tween.

05:38.266 --> 05:41.233
LIZZIE: <i>"Dear Clean, get your friend</i>
<i>some new cool perfume.</i>

05:41.300 --> 05:44.900
<i>"That way, you get to sidestep</i>
<i>a potentially stinky situation."</i>

05:45.333 --> 05:48.200
Uh, Kate, have you tried
this new peppermint perfume?

05:48.266 --> 05:49.467
I got it at the mall.

05:50.767 --> 05:51.967
Hmm, pretty.

05:53.867 --> 05:55.100
Here, I bought two.

05:56.633 --> 05:58.166
[UPBEAT MUSIC]

06:29.867 --> 06:31.133
Ooh!

06:32.767 --> 06:36.400
You know, I haven't been
to recess in, like, three weeks.

06:36.467 --> 06:37.900
I'm usually in detention.

06:38.934 --> 06:42.133
See, there is some benefits
to sharing the blame with Adam.

06:42.400 --> 06:44.734
Yeah, but I hate sharing the glory.

06:44.900 --> 06:46.734
Maybe there's enough gags
to go around.

06:46.867 --> 06:49.266
Forget it. I mean, I'm different.

06:49.500 --> 06:52.467
I'm better. I am the king.

06:53.500 --> 06:55.567
Just as long as you know
when to let go.

06:59.000 --> 07:00.300
Adam Burton.

07:00.400 --> 07:03.033
Matt McGuire, you finally noticed me.

07:03.367 --> 07:05.700
How can I not? Okay, fess up, Burton.

07:05.767 --> 07:08.266
You totally stole
my burping gag this morning.

07:08.333 --> 07:11.734
I'm sorry. You were late, and well,
I'm just a huge fan of your work.

07:11.800 --> 07:13.266
You're a comic genius.

07:13.333 --> 07:16.166
Well, I... I do try.

07:16.467 --> 07:19.100
I can only hope that one day,
I'll be as good as you.

07:19.567 --> 07:22.367
Maybe someday I'll share
some of my secrets with you.

07:23.867 --> 07:26.000
Okay, class, settle down

07:26.066 --> 07:28.633
and turn your history books
to chapter 12.

07:30.834 --> 07:33.200
[SQUELCHING]

07:37.400 --> 07:38.667
Mr. McGuire,

07:38.934 --> 07:41.533
I'm sure you had
something to do with this.

07:41.900 --> 07:43.667
I... I didn't.

07:43.734 --> 07:45.433
[ALL GASPING]

07:45.533 --> 07:46.800
I did it.

07:46.867 --> 07:48.700
Twice in one day, Mr. Burton.

07:49.166 --> 07:52.033
Are you trying to surpass
our Mr. McGuire here?

07:53.000 --> 07:54.400
I thought you looked up to me.

07:55.066 --> 07:57.033
So young, so gullible.

07:57.934 --> 08:00.233
How did you manage
to stay on top for so long?

08:01.233 --> 08:03.400
I guess I'll be headed
to the principal's office.

08:08.967 --> 08:09.967
[SQUELCHING]

08:12.066 --> 08:13.166
[GRUNTS]

08:13.233 --> 08:14.400
I'm stuck!

08:15.500 --> 08:16.633
[LAUGHTER]

08:16.734 --> 08:19.533
Retire, while you still
have your dignity.

08:20.233 --> 08:21.500
[GRUNTING]

08:23.800 --> 08:25.633
Hey, Lizzie, can I get
a second with you?

08:27.300 --> 08:29.600
Yeah, sure. Are you okay?

08:30.166 --> 08:31.200
Pretty good.

08:31.934 --> 08:34.834
If "pretty good"
and "covered in leftovers"
are the same thing,

08:34.900 --> 08:37.233
I'd hate to see
what "not so good" looks like.

08:37.367 --> 08:39.033
Well, what happened?

08:39.967 --> 08:42.066
Dear Lizzie, I've got a big problem.

08:42.166 --> 08:43.367
Her name is Sheryl.

08:44.600 --> 08:45.600
[GROWLS]

08:48.100 --> 08:50.133
Sheryl is always picking on me.

08:50.300 --> 08:52.967
Now, normally, I'm a girl that
can take care of herself,

08:53.033 --> 08:54.600
but Sheryl just can't leave me alone.

08:55.000 --> 08:57.266
I tried ignoring her,
but nothing seems to work.

08:58.900 --> 09:00.333
Signed, Fed Up.

09:01.066 --> 09:02.600
Any of that ring a bell?

09:03.967 --> 09:05.133
Yeah.

09:05.800 --> 09:08.333
LIZZIE: <i>"Dear Fed Up,</i>
<i>all bullies are cowards.</i>

09:08.800 --> 09:11.533
<i>"Just stand up to her once </i>
<i>and she'll leave you alone."</i>

09:12.100 --> 09:14.700
VERUCA: <i>So I took your advice,</i>
<i>and you know what? </i>

09:15.100 --> 09:16.400
<i>Bullies have friends.</i>

09:16.734 --> 09:18.000
<i>When you're outnumbered three to one,</i>

09:18.066 --> 09:19.633
<i>it's kind of hard </i>
<i>to stand up for yourself.</i>

09:21.266 --> 09:23.033
-So they beat you up?
-No.

09:23.500 --> 09:26.133
I just spent the last hour
hiding in the cafeteria garbage.

09:26.433 --> 09:27.834
Veruca, I'm so sorry.

09:27.900 --> 09:29.900
You know what? You really should be.

09:30.200 --> 09:33.500
I just thought you might want to know
that your advice has consequences.

09:33.567 --> 09:36.600
-Veruca, I didn't think...
-Yeah, you didn't think.

09:40.066 --> 09:42.200
And nothing gets out goulash!

09:45.500 --> 09:46.500
[SIGHS]

09:47.200 --> 09:48.400
Dear Lizzie,

09:48.467 --> 09:51.734
what do you do
when the advice columnist
runs out of advice?

09:55.200 --> 09:56.734
-Hey, Gordo.
-Hey, Lizzie.

09:56.867 --> 09:59.867
I got Principal Tweedy to give us
some more space on the school server,

09:59.934 --> 10:01.967
so this week you can make
your column even longer.

10:02.166 --> 10:03.400
That's great,

10:03.500 --> 10:05.700
but, um, I quit.

10:05.900 --> 10:07.633
[STAMMERS] You can't quit.

10:08.767 --> 10:10.000
I think I just did.

10:10.166 --> 10:12.333
Gordo, I just don't think
I'm cut out for this job.

10:12.600 --> 10:14.500
I mean, Veruca followed my advice

10:14.567 --> 10:17.266
and it got her hiding
in a trash can for like an hour.

10:17.333 --> 10:19.400
So? You win some, and you lose some.

10:19.467 --> 10:21.233
The trash can in the school cafeteria.

10:21.333 --> 10:23.166
Ew. I can see your point,

10:23.233 --> 10:25.100
but that still doesn't change the fact

10:25.166 --> 10:28.467
that I need to get a new edition
of the e-zine out tomorrow,

10:28.533 --> 10:29.934
so what are you going to do?

10:30.867 --> 10:33.633
I want to run home and hide
in my bedroom under the covers

10:33.700 --> 10:35.567
with hot cocoa and Mr. Snuggles.

10:35.934 --> 10:37.166
I don't know. I just...

10:37.233 --> 10:39.700
I can't think.
There's so much pressure.

10:40.166 --> 10:44.767
Snapping under pressure is absolutely
and totally understandable, Lizzie.

10:47.200 --> 10:50.133
Oh, my gosh. Do you think
that's what happened to Ms. Dew?

10:50.233 --> 10:51.934
I don't want to go on sabbatical!

10:52.600 --> 10:54.100
I'm so sorry, Gordo.

10:54.166 --> 10:55.266
Can't you find someone else?

10:55.333 --> 10:58.166
Not this late in the game.
Look, I'll make you a deal.

10:58.233 --> 11:00.734
Now, I have to upload the new edition
of the e-zine tomorrow morning.

11:01.333 --> 11:04.166
If you answer just one more letter,
then you can hang up your pen.

11:04.900 --> 11:06.633
Um, I don't use a pen.

11:06.900 --> 11:09.467
You know, I could write
an advice column.

11:09.533 --> 11:10.600
Oh...

11:10.700 --> 11:14.900
My first article could be
the benefits of wearing tin foil hats.

11:15.300 --> 11:16.333
Let me know.

11:19.467 --> 11:22.000
If Ms. Dew writes our advice column,

11:22.066 --> 11:23.867
I'm going to have
to take a sabbatical.

11:25.433 --> 11:26.600
[SIGHS]

11:27.066 --> 11:29.033
Today I take back my crown.

11:29.500 --> 11:31.934
You're washed up, champ. Forget it.

11:32.834 --> 11:36.934
Uh, you know, you could be
a little more supportive.

11:43.066 --> 11:47.266
So you think you can steal
my material and get away with it?

11:47.333 --> 11:51.600
I take your old, tired gags
and make them funny again.

11:51.667 --> 11:56.600
Oh, yeah? Well, I got
a couple new pranks up my sleeve.

12:00.333 --> 12:03.800
By the way,
have you checked your desk?

12:05.233 --> 12:07.233
Wait a minute, this isn't my desk.

12:08.300 --> 12:09.567
Somebody switched them.

12:14.266 --> 12:16.633
Oh, yeah, that was me.

12:16.834 --> 12:17.900
-[SQUELCHING]
-[GRUNTS]

12:21.533 --> 12:25.200
I'll get you back
if it's the last thing I do.

12:25.900 --> 12:29.500
Today we'll be learning about
Newton's laws of motion.

12:34.066 --> 12:35.667
[LAUGHTER]

12:37.033 --> 12:40.100
I believe you know
your way to the office, Mr. Burton.

12:43.500 --> 12:45.500
Wait, it's my prank.

12:45.567 --> 12:47.066
It's my fault.

12:47.400 --> 12:50.567
I'm the funny one!

12:51.300 --> 12:52.767
Stick a fork in you.

12:53.333 --> 12:54.600
You're done.

12:59.734 --> 13:00.800
[SIGHS]

13:01.233 --> 13:03.133
One more letter. I can do this.

13:03.266 --> 13:05.367
No one will end up
hiding in the garbage.

13:06.367 --> 13:08.000
-"Dear Lizzie..."
-ETHAN: Dear Lizzie,

13:08.133 --> 13:10.133
people think that I'm not very bright.

13:10.333 --> 13:12.600
They think I'm just a pretty face.

13:17.633 --> 13:20.867
How could I get looks beyond my looks?

13:21.467 --> 13:23.700
Signed, More Than Good Hair.

13:24.166 --> 13:25.800
LIZZIE: <i>"Dear Smarter,</i>

13:26.400 --> 13:29.600
<i>"you need to do something </i>
<i>to make them take you more seriously.</i>

13:30.333 --> 13:34.166
<i>"Stop concentrating on your looks </i>
<i>and hit the books."</i>

13:35.500 --> 13:38.400
[SCREAMING] No!

13:43.266 --> 13:44.967
[GASPS] Ethan, what did you do?

13:45.200 --> 13:46.700
What you told me to do.

13:46.834 --> 13:48.467
That hair was nothing but trouble.

13:48.533 --> 13:50.233
Plus, now my brain can get some air.

13:50.300 --> 13:51.433
[SCREAMING]

13:51.533 --> 13:52.567
[GASPS]

13:52.633 --> 13:54.133
Delete! Delete!

13:54.834 --> 13:56.333
Maybe the next letter.

13:57.400 --> 13:58.467
[KEYBOARD CLACKING]

13:58.533 --> 14:01.066
-"Dear Lizzie..."
-Dear Lizzie, I'm popular.

14:01.166 --> 14:04.133
I'm pretty.
I have incredible fashion sense.

14:06.200 --> 14:08.266
So, why aren't I happier?

14:08.767 --> 14:10.533
Signed, Baffled Beauty.

14:10.834 --> 14:12.100
LIZZIE: <i>"Dear Baffled,</i>

14:12.533 --> 14:15.934
<i>"when you stop thinking about yourself</i>
<i>and start thinking more about others,</i>

14:16.033 --> 14:17.967
<i>"you'll be happier, I promise."</i>

14:18.367 --> 14:20.934
[SIGHS] Peace Corps, here I come.

14:23.367 --> 14:24.867
[TRIBESMEN GRUNTING]

14:25.800 --> 14:28.934
We can provide your village
with food, clothing, and clean water.

14:29.000 --> 14:30.567
[TRIBESMAN GRUNTING]

14:33.200 --> 14:35.867
Oh, that's so thoughtful.
I haven't Jacuzzied in months.

14:39.767 --> 14:41.300
TRIBESMAN: Mmm. [CHUCKLES]

14:43.967 --> 14:47.300
[SIGHS] There's got to be
one question here
that doesn't end badly.

14:47.567 --> 14:49.767
Although the Kate fantasy
wasn't so bad.

14:49.834 --> 14:50.934
[SLURPS] Blergh!

14:51.200 --> 14:52.200
Hmm.

14:54.200 --> 14:55.600
"Dear Lizzie..."

14:55.734 --> 14:58.867
Dear Lizzie, while I am brilliant,
witty, and debonair,

14:58.934 --> 15:01.767
the other kids at school
don't seem to realize this.

15:01.867 --> 15:03.500
[LAUGHS] Tudgeman.

15:05.967 --> 15:07.867
How can I get
the other kids at school to like me?

15:08.300 --> 15:10.266
Signed, A Captain with No Shipmates.

15:11.867 --> 15:14.600
LIZZIE: <i>"Dear Captain, if you make </i>
<i>more of an effort to join in,</i>

15:14.667 --> 15:16.367
<i>"the other kids will take notice.</i>

15:17.066 --> 15:19.133
<i>"The way to make a friend </i>
<i>is to be a friend."</i>

15:19.400 --> 15:20.500
Hi.

15:20.567 --> 15:23.533
Um, I'd like to sign up
for the Pep Club.

15:24.000 --> 15:26.967
Sorry, but we've already reached
our dork quotient for the year.

15:28.033 --> 15:29.200
Right.

15:31.500 --> 15:34.000
You know, one day,
I'm going to start my own club.

15:34.667 --> 15:36.033
[ALL LAUGHING]

15:39.800 --> 15:43.200
Mr. President, you cannot let
Dr. Tudgeman destroy the universe.

15:43.333 --> 15:45.433
How hard was it
to let him join Pep Club?

15:45.900 --> 15:49.333
Losers bent on universal destruction
do not belong in the Pep Club.

15:49.400 --> 15:50.567
Why did I marry you?

15:50.633 --> 15:54.734
Because I am the best-looking
First Lady since... since ever.

15:56.700 --> 15:57.867
Send in my advisor.

16:02.266 --> 16:03.934
Lizzie, we have a situation here.

16:04.000 --> 16:05.333
Yes, Mr. President, sir?

16:07.233 --> 16:08.333
[DRAMATIC MUSIC]

16:10.200 --> 16:13.166
<i>I want $2 billion.</i>

16:14.734 --> 16:15.867
Who said that?

16:17.033 --> 16:18.934
<i>Over here, you doofus.</i>

16:19.767 --> 16:22.233
<i>Oh, Lizzie, I've been</i>
<i>meaning to thank you.</i>

16:22.567 --> 16:26.367
<i>Founding the Evil Geniuses </i>
<i>Bent on Universal Destruction Club</i>

16:26.433 --> 16:28.734
<i>was the best idea you ever had.</i>

16:29.500 --> 16:32.200
But I didn't mean
for it to end up this way.

16:32.300 --> 16:35.266
<i>I'd like the money by say, noonish.</i>

16:36.700 --> 16:38.033
<i>Ciao.</i>

16:38.133 --> 16:39.734
[EVIL LAUGH]

16:39.834 --> 16:42.133
[SCREAMING]

16:43.100 --> 16:46.367
That's it.
This amateur advice columnist
is going to the pros.

16:48.500 --> 16:50.333
Mom, Dad, I need your help.

16:50.500 --> 16:53.467
-You're asking us for advice?
-Intentionally?

16:54.133 --> 16:55.133
Yes.

16:55.400 --> 16:57.767
[CHURCH MUSIC PLAYING]

17:02.166 --> 17:03.834
What's wrong, honey?

17:03.900 --> 17:07.100
Well, I've been giving people advice
and they've been taking it.

17:07.200 --> 17:11.300
Everybody's been really happy
and everything's been
going good, until...

17:11.367 --> 17:14.700
Until some of your good advice
landed someone in a bad situation?

17:17.600 --> 17:18.700
Yeah.

17:18.834 --> 17:20.200
How did you know that?

17:21.467 --> 17:23.900
It doesn't take a genius
to see where this is going.

17:24.567 --> 17:28.667
Lizzie, you can't be expected
to control every single thing
that happens.

17:28.734 --> 17:31.300
You just have to give
the best advice you can

17:31.367 --> 17:32.734
and hope it works out.

17:34.567 --> 17:35.633
What he said.

17:36.600 --> 17:37.900
That's the thing about dads.

17:38.133 --> 17:40.633
You think they're clueless,
and then they just surprise you.

17:41.033 --> 17:42.800
I just feel kind of frozen.

17:42.867 --> 17:45.400
And I promised Gordo
that I'd answer one more letter.

17:45.533 --> 17:49.166
Okay. So pretend
you're one of your readers

17:49.233 --> 17:52.734
and if you were to give yourself
advice right now,

17:52.867 --> 17:54.300
what would you say?

17:55.000 --> 17:57.200
I guess I'd just say, sit back,

17:57.266 --> 18:00.066
relax and answer
the next letter that comes my way.

18:00.133 --> 18:01.467
Off you go, then.

18:01.834 --> 18:03.033
Thanks, Dad.

18:05.700 --> 18:07.900
I know. I'm good.

18:10.367 --> 18:11.467
[SIGHS]

18:11.567 --> 18:12.567
[COMPUTER BEEPS]

18:13.567 --> 18:14.900
This is the one.

18:15.166 --> 18:16.333
[KEYBOARD CLACKING]

18:16.834 --> 18:18.734
-Adam. Adam.
-What do you want?

18:19.266 --> 18:23.100
I wanted to tell you
that I give up. You win.

18:23.233 --> 18:27.100
I will have to be happy with
simply following in your footsteps.

18:27.166 --> 18:28.367
As it should be.

18:29.266 --> 18:31.000
After you. I insist.

18:36.533 --> 18:42.066
You know, McGuire, I expect more than
a bucket over the door gag from you.

18:49.767 --> 18:50.934
-[GRUNTS]
-Like that?

18:51.600 --> 18:53.066
-Just like that?
-McGuire!

18:54.900 --> 18:57.834
It's payback time, Mr. Burton.

19:16.166 --> 19:19.767
Mr. McGuire, this has your name
written all over it.

19:20.367 --> 19:23.166
Why, yes. Thank you for noticing.

19:23.233 --> 19:26.433
I think you and the principal
need to have a little chat.

19:27.166 --> 19:28.533
I'll show myself out.

19:28.900 --> 19:29.900
Mm-hmm.

19:29.967 --> 19:31.400
Welcome back, Matt.

19:33.333 --> 19:35.333
-[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]
-[CROWD CHEERING]

19:45.967 --> 19:48.433
-Hey, did you get my column?
-Yep.

19:48.500 --> 19:51.200
And I see you had it in you
to answer one last letter.

19:51.400 --> 19:53.700
Well, I couldn't let
Confused Guy down.

19:54.233 --> 19:55.533
You didn't.

19:56.166 --> 19:58.066
-What?
-Nothing.

19:58.133 --> 20:00.667
Um, looks like everything's
ready to go here.

20:07.633 --> 20:09.200
Dear Lizzie,

20:09.266 --> 20:12.834
I think I may like my best friend
as more than a friend.

20:16.800 --> 20:18.600
What? Do I, like,
have something on my face?

20:18.767 --> 20:20.967
No. You're perfect.

20:22.233 --> 20:25.266
What should I do?
Signed, Confused Guy.

20:26.633 --> 20:29.233
LIZZIE: <i>"Dear Confused.</i>
<i>I wish I could tell you what to do,</i>

20:29.300 --> 20:30.667
<i>"but I can't."</i>

20:32.233 --> 20:34.433
Hey, guys. You ready to go?

20:34.500 --> 20:36.033
-Yeah.
-Where are you going?

20:36.100 --> 20:37.834
Oh, I'm going to walk Veruca to class.

20:37.900 --> 20:39.600
Standing up to her bully
didn't really work,

20:39.700 --> 20:42.266
but we did learn
that there are safety in numbers.

20:43.033 --> 20:44.200
Come on, we're going to be late.

20:46.033 --> 20:49.533
LIZZIE: <i>"All I can say is</i>
<i>just follow your heart.</i>
<i>It'll tell you what's right."</i>

20:49.700 --> 20:50.834
Lizzie, wait.

20:52.600 --> 20:55.834
Um, there's something
I need to tell you.

20:56.800 --> 20:57.867
Yeah?

21:03.300 --> 21:04.500
You give great advice.

21:25.266 --> 21:26.300
MALE CREW MEMBER: Marker.

21:27.166 --> 21:28.367
Shoot!

21:29.400 --> 21:30.500
Ah!

21:33.700 --> 21:34.734
[SNEEZES]

21:35.133 --> 21:36.800
A lot of practice.

21:37.600 --> 21:39.166
-Am I jumping lines?
-CREW MEMBERS: Yes.

21:39.700 --> 21:43.900
We did learn that lucky numbers
walk together or something like that.

21:44.600 --> 21:47.667
I just spent the hal...
the last hour hiding in the caf...

21:48.000 --> 21:50.533
A stroke of brillan... bril-brillance.

21:50.600 --> 21:51.667
[BABBLES]

21:51.867 --> 21:53.700
Memorize everything about this moment.

21:54.100 --> 21:55.467
Gordo just called me...

21:56.767 --> 21:58.200
MALE CREW MEMBER: And cut it! Great!

22:01.533 --> 22:03.500
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]
